column4: <content>Murder of Innocents: Alba. The commander of the soldiers with his long white beard nearest to Alba portrait as it appears in the anonymous engraving of Jacques Jonghelincks' statue erected in the Antwerp citadel 1568, destroyed by Requesens 1574. Repr. e.g. in [Henri] PIRENNE, Hist. de Belgique [= Histoire de Belgique des origines à nos jours, Bruxelles: Renaissance du Livre, 1948-1952] illustr[ated] quarto ed. 194..[sic], II, p. 273 (B[ritish] M[useum] 9414.m.4). This is certainly the prototype of the painting; cf. also (though here he looks different) the anonymous satyrical print showing Alba seated above the corpses of Egmont & Hoorn, at his side a centaure with 3 heads (Cardinals Guise, Lorraine, Granvelle). Alba devours a child. The inscription; [verso] in Flemish & French says: [... ] reprod. p. 274: A portrait of Alba (repr. p. 289) by an unknown painter (Coll. of Duke of Berwick & Alba, Madrid) said to represent him of the age of 74, shows him with long white beard.</content>
